 Morrison, Pierre Cardin, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, and Josephine Baker.I Always Knew is an intimate and vivid portrait of Chase-Riboud’s life as told through the letters she wrote to her mother, Vivian Mae, between 1957 and 1991. In candid detail, Chase-Riboud tells her mother about her life in Europe, her work as an artist, her romances, and her journeys around the world, from Western and Eastern Europe to the Middle East, Africa, the Soviet Union, China, and Mongolia.By turns brilliant and naïve, passionate and tender, poignant and funny, these letters show Chase-Riboud in the process of becoming who she is and who she might become. But what emerges most of all is the powerful story of a unique and remarkable relationship between a talented, ambitious, and courageous daughter and her adored mother.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American artistsvBiography. 0aAfrican American artistsvCorrespondence. 0aArtistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aArtistszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 0aWomen artistszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen artistszUnited StatesvCorrespondence. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Artists, Architects, Photographers.2bisacsh  aAcupuncture.  aAfrica.  aAgnes Martin.  aAlexander Calder.  aAnnecy.  aArt dealer.  aAstrology.  aAuguste Comte.  aAvignon.  aAward.  aBen Shahn.  aBlouse.  aBollinger.  aBrazilians.  aCarlotta (The Phantom of the Opera).  aCarpet.  aChicken salad.  aClothing.  aCocktail party.  aCommunist revolution.  aCorn on the cob.  aCurator.  aDe facto.  aDemagogue.  aDestination Unknown (novel).  aDeviled egg.  aDirect flight.  aDisease.  aDo the Right Thing.  aDoctor of Philosophy.  aDominique de Menil.  aDust jacket.  aErik (The Phantom of the Opera).  aFederal government of the United States.  